  <h2 id="how-we-evaluate">How we evaluate</h2>
  <p>For this roundup, we focused on real buyer outcomes: cleaner flavor in the cup, fewer dialing headaches, and less daily mess. Each grinder was compared by burr consistency potential, grind-range usefulness for different brew methods, retention/static behavior, cleaning burden, and overall price-to-performance balance under a strict $200 cap.</p>
  <p>We weighted grind range differently based on use case. A grinder that only performs well in drip or pour over can still rank highly for budget households, but it cannot lead the list when buyers want one machine for both filter and espresso. In this price band, adjustment precision is often the difference between repeatable espresso and frustrating shot variance.</p>
  <p>Retention and static were treated as practical quality factors, not cosmetic details. Cheap grinders that spray fines everywhere or hold stale coffee in the chute lose points because they add friction to every brew day. Small improvements in grounds handling can matter as much as burr geometry when you are brewing before work and need a predictable routine.</p>
  <p>We also considered maintenance burden over time. Some grinders are easy to open, brush, and return to the same setting, while others require more fiddling. A strong value pick should not just produce a good cup on day one; it should remain easy enough to maintain that you keep using it consistently.</p>
  <p>Finally, we compared relative value inside three practical tiers: under $100, $100 to $149, and $150 to $200. This makes recommendations clearer for buyers who already know their spending ceiling. Instead of one generic winner, you get the best fit for your budget, brew style, and tolerance for daily workflow complexity.</p>

  <h2 id="product-reviews">Product reviews by use case</h2>

  <h3>1) Baratza Encore ESP</h3>
  <ProductCard
    title={products[0].name}
    image={{ src: products[0].image, alt: products[0].imageAlt, width: 500, height: 500 }}
    badge={products[0].badge}
