  <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Buyers upgrading from blade grinders who mainly brew drip, pour over, or French press and want reliable results near the lower end of the budget.</p>
  <ProsCons
    pros={[
      'Strong value for filter-focused brewing.',
      'Simple controls and low learning curve.',
      'Easy to keep clean for daily use.',
    ]}
    cons={[
      'Limited precision for repeatable espresso dialing.',
      'Can produce extra static in dry environments.',
    ]}
  />
  <p>OXO Brew is the best under-$100 style option when your priority is consistency without complexity. It delivers a clear upgrade over blade grinders and does not require a long adjustment-learning phase. For batch brew households, that matters more than having an espresso-first feature set you may never use.</p>
  <p>If your plan is strictly filter coffee, this grinder keeps cost low while still producing noticeably cleaner cups than entry blade alternatives. If espresso is a near-term goal, however, move up to Encore ESP, Opus, or SK40 for better fine-range control.</p>
  <p><CtaButton href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B07CSKGLMM/ref=nosim?tag=coffee-site-20" external>Check Price on Amazon</CtaButton></p>

